A longer index finger than a ring finger means a lower risk of developing cancer
Men whose index finger is longer than the ring finger are obviously at a lower risk of developing prostate cancer.
This is the surprising result of a study published Wednesday by the British Journal of Cancer.
This is supposed to be related to the level of the male hormone testosterone.
“Our results show that the relative length of the fingers can serve as a simple test for the risk of prostate cancer, especially in men up to sixty,” said Ros Eeles, a professor at the Cancer Research Institute at the University of Warwick.
The finger could thus help determine which men should necessarily undergo a prostate cancer test, especially if there are genetic risks or other risk factors, such as familial health burdens, added Mrs. Eeles.
Between 1994 and 2009, she and her colleagues in Britain tracked more than 1,500 patients with prostate cancer, but also 3,000 healthy men.
In more than half of the study participants, the index finger of the right hand was shorter than the ring finger.
These men had the same probability of prostate cancer as 19 percent of men whose ring and index fingers were the same length.
In men whose index finger was longer than the ring finger, however, this risk decreased by 33 percent, and in men up to sixty by 87 percent.
The ratio of the length of the two fingers mentioned, which are formed already at prenatal age, obviously reflects the different levels of sex hormones to which the child was exposed in the womb.
Less testosterone corresponds to a longer index finger.
Previous research has shown that it is testosterone that accelerates the growth of prostate cancer.
V<0xC3><0xA1>clav Pa<0xC4><0x8D>es, a leading Czech geneticist and former chairman of the Academy of Sciences, told <0xC4><0x8C>TK that the study was known to him as volatile, but he did not consider the relationship between finger length and cancer risk "totally proven".
