Two facts are particularly prominent in this year's September and October surveys.
First, the good mood in Latin America
and, secondly, the growing interest in democracy and its most important institutions.
In many countries along the South American Pacific coast, the democratic movement has increased significantly (see Table 1).
In Peru, for example, where the economy has grown by about 6% annually since 2002, the number of democracy advocates rose from 40% in 2005 to 61% this year.
This trend can also be seen in Mexico, where the economy has recovered since the strong break-in last year.
But only half of the respondents in Mexico and Brazil, the most populous countries in the region, are convinced Democrats, which lowers the regional average (see Figure 2).
Approximately 44% of respondents said they were satisfied with their country's democratic practice, which is as many as last year, but 25% more than in 2001 (Diagram 3).
Approximately 34% trust the Congress of their country and 45% of their government. Both values correspond to last year, but show a significant increase compared to 2003 (17% and 24%, respectively).
A decade ago, the economic crisis in Latin America undermined efforts to achieve more democracy.
This continued during the global economic crisis, possibly due to the fact that the countries of Latin America experienced only a short period of recession and quickly recovered.
In addition, the poor have been caught up by a stronger social network.
(According to reports by the UN Economic Commission for Latin America this week, the poverty rate in Latin America rose only slightly in 2009 and fell by 32% again this year.)
However, there are significant differences in mood from country to country (see Figure 4).
Brazil’s strong economy and the popularity of the separating president Luiz In<0xC3><0xA1>cio Lula da Silva is reflected in a widespread thought of progress.
In Mexico and Central America, where the recession was more noticeable and violent crimes have increased, this is less the case.
For the second time since the survey began, many Latin American respondents see crime in their country as a bigger problem than unemployment (see Figure 5).
Approximately 31% say that they or a family member have been victims of a crime in the last year, but compared to 38% in the last year, the values have fallen, reaching the lowest level since 1995.
Increasing economic performance is reflected in stronger support for the private and market economy: 71% of respondents across the region said that the private economy is essential for development, compared to 56% in 2007 (see Figure 6).
Approximately 58% said that only the market economy can make progress in their country, compared with 47% last year.
Interestingly, 62% of respondents in Venezuela retained this view (and 80% are for a private sector), although its left-wing president, Hugo Ch<0xC3><0xA1>vez, nationalizes many private companies.
According to 19% of respondents (18% last year) Brazil has the largest weight in the region, followed by the United States (9%, unchanged since last year) and Venezuela (9% compared to 11% last year).
In contrast, respondents in Mexico and most Central American countries see the United States as the most influential country, with this role being taken over by Venezuela in the Dominican Republic and Nicaragua.
