Arsenic-resistant microbe could enable new life forms on Earth or elsewhere
The discovery of a foreign species of bacteria that can live from arsenic, among others, opens up new possibilities for new life forms on Earth and elsewhere.
Although scientists have discovered this unusual bacterium here on Earth, it is, in their view, a sign that life is possible even without the elements previously considered vital.
"This organism has two options."
"It needs to grow either phosphorus or arsenic."
“That makes it something very special, even though it’s almost a kind of ‘foreign’ form of life,” said Paul C.W. Davies of Arizona State University and co-author of the report, which appears on Thursday in the online edition of the journal Science.
So far, six main elements have been considered vital - carbon, hydrogen, nitrogen, oxygen, phosphorus and sulfur.
But as the scientists found out, the bacterium in Mono Lake, California, grows even further when it replaces phosphorus with arsenic.
“You wonder what else is possible,” said report co-author Ariel D. Anbar of Arizona State University.
The discovery is an important step in the search for extraterrestrial life, as scientists need to recognize life and its forms, according to Anbar.
The study deals with microbes found on Earth.
The announcement of a press conference in which no details of the discovery were announced led to widespread speculation on the Internet that the report of the discovery of extraterrestrial life could act.
This is not the case.
The discovery "shows that organisms in other planetary systems can initiate biochemical processes with the help of other elements and that the 'standard elements', which we think are absolutely vital, are not necessarily fixed," explained Charles Cockell, Professor of Planetary and Space Sciences at the Mileagen University of Ke Space Research Institute.
Cockel was not part of the research team.
“This work is a novelty because it shows that in basic biochemical processes and structures one element can be replaced by another,” Cockell added.
This discovery was not accidental.
Felisa Wolfe-Simon of NASA’s Astrobiological Institute, who led the study, chose Mono Lake because of its high arsenic content.
Because arsenic and phosphorus are chemically similar, she assumed that microbes that are both exposed may be able to replace one element by the other.
“The toxicity of arsenic is primarily due to its chemical behavior similar to that of phosphorus.”
"This makes it difficult for organisms to distinguish one element from the other."
“But the difference is so big that arsenic works differently than phosphorus, it gets into our biochemical system, where it lubricates almost everything,” explains Anbar.
The researchers exposed the GFAJ-1 bacterium to an increasing concentration of arsenic. It adapted and grew.
Although the microbe grows better in phosphorus, but that it can also survive in arsenic, it shows that an arsenic-based life form can occur naturally, either on Earth or on another planet or moon, where arsenic is more common.
According to Jamie S. Foster, professor of microbiology at the University of Florida, the idea that phosphorus can be replaced by arsenic is not new, but so far there has been no working example.
Arsenic was more common in the early Earth years, she says, which is why science has assumed that early life forms have used it.
"This gives reason to assume that life may have evolved differently than it did in the early Earth age," said Forster, who was not a member of Wolfe-Simon's research team.
The research was supported by NASA, the Ministry of Energy and the National Health Authorities.
