Can courtesy connect the separator?
After a campaign of mockery and negativity, this week little politeness broke out in Washington.
Is it the omen of genuine bilateral cooperation or a moment of illusion before you quickly return to the struggle of the parties in the capital?
The meeting on Tuesday between President Obama and congressional leaders did not bring a breakthrough in the major issues that had to be dealt with during the so-called "lame duck session", the session at the end of a period of government in which no decisions are made.
After all, it was neither a polite discussion between two different sides nor an observation of their shared responsibility to govern, but rather an empty episode of a party point-gathering.
The president’s public meeting of the deficit commission on Wednesday was also civilized, despite the political differences that continue between the members.
It seems clear that a close interaction over a period of months creates mutual respect, which obscures the ideological gap that continues to separate members from each other.
This is hardly enough to claim that a new era of cooperation has begun.
Both sides are now in a test phase – where one is asking for signs of cooperation and compromise from the other, while trying to weigh the limits of public opinion and the patience of the voters after a re-run of the party war.
Therefore, the meeting on Tuesday itself and its assessment by the participants were limited to a minimum of claims or accusations.
The philosophical differences between Obama and the Republicans are too big and too deep to expect a rapid change in the atmosphere that has prevailed over the past two years.
Whether it’s taxes, donations, health, or expectations, the two sides are miles away from each other.
Lastly, the November election in Washington voted mildly, at least for a short time.
“No question, the pitch has changed,” said Pete Wehner, an official representative of the Bush administration who is now working for the Ethics and Public Policy Center.
“This is inevitable after elections.
Elections arouse party passions that are dying again.
And that's good."
In some issues, especially those that are on the agenda of the “lame duck session,” Republicans and Democrats have hardly any choice but to find a solution.”
Bush’s tax cuts end at the end of the year, and no one is in favour of that.
Both sides want to find a way to get some or even all of them, whether temporary or permanent.
Similarly, a compromise is to be expected with regard to the increased unemployment wages, if only because the Republicans can’t afford to believe the favored tax cuts for the rich, while they refuse to support the unemployed workers.
After the meeting at the White House on Tuesday, optimism has risen that one can agree on these issues during the "lame duck session" and at the same time ratify the New START Treaty.
But William Glaston of the Brookings Institution warns that a successful cooperation on urgent issues of the lame duck session does not necessarily have to lead to a permanent cooperation of the parties when the new 112th Congress is convened in January.
Instead, he says, a phase of non-conformity is more likely, perhaps even inevitable.
“After the things that need to be done are done, this short-term psychology will turn into confrontation,” he said.
Wehner is also skeptical – and this skepticism is shared by many – that courtesy leads to true cooperation.
“I see a lot of what is happening from today to 2012, as pre-fighting, or shadow boxes, for the main event of 2012,” he said.
The reasons for this have a lot to do with the creation of the new Republican majority in the White House and the tea party voters who served their formation.
As worried as the Republican leaders may be about being too high on poker, they know that they must try to keep their promises to lower government spending and override the health reform.
These partisan lines will already become clear in the first responses to the recommendations of the deficit commission, which include a tax reform and raising some taxes, as well as raising the retirement age and lowering government spending.
Vice-Chairmen Alan Simpson and Erskine Bowles have taken over one of the most difficult jobs in Washington and, in their own judgment, have pushed so hard to put the deficit issue on the public agenda that they can no longer be ignored.
But they need within the commission 14 of the 18 votes to make their plan the official recommendation and they struggle very hard to get even close to that number.
The greatest resistance is found in the elected representatives of the body, since in financial matters, at least today, there is little room or sympathy for compromise.
Galston predicts two phases in the struggle between the White House and the Republicans in Congress.
The first fight will take place next year in the form of party clashes, when Republicans challenge Obama in terms of the state budget, taxation, and health care system, later followed by a phase of greater bipartisan cooperation.
What will lead to this change?
The public opinion.
It is proven that, despite the partyliness of the current election, the majority of Americans still want the two parties to work together.
If confrontation leads to a dead end, as happened in 1995, then both parties must pay close attention to the public reaction.
Whoever is condemned to lose will have to change course and seek compromise.
In fact, this may be an optimistic viewpoint.
Partyism and polarization are bigger today than in the mid-1990s, and they seem to be a larger ideological gap between Obama and the Republicans in Congress than it was between President Bill Clinton and the Republicans in his time.
At the same time, the activists of both parties see 2010 as a pure example for a far more consistent 2012 election.
In this sense, the courtesy shown this week may be welcomed by many Americans.
But on both sides, it will require much more effort to find a common denominator in the issues that still separate the two from each other.
