Sport and regular walking
Tricks like those of Alonso and Ramos in the game against the Ajax show inventiveness, but not the will to bypass a sanction.
The alleged exclusion of two Real Madrid players (Xabi Alonso and Sergio Ramos) in the November 23 match against Ajax in the Champions League resulted in a lot of ink spilling over whether it was an unsporting act or not and whether both players should be sanctioned by UEFA.
As is generally known, the two players lost time a few minutes before the end of the game (their team had already clearly won) and played several fouls so that the referee showed them the second yellow card.
In this way, and as Real Madrid would lead his group, the two players will meet the prescribed penalty in the next league game against the Auxerre and thus enter the next game phase without cards.
Finally, the UEFA Disciplinary Committee punished the club's coach, José Mourinho, with two games and the players involved with different amounts of money.
The provocation of a yellow card under such or similar circumstances is not a new practice, it is more common in the world of football.
It is so widespread that it is part of the ethos – the unwritten but in this sport followed rules.
Part of the debate that arose about the case is due to the fact that a team of the football club Real Madrid (who in his anthem of nobility and honor and on other occasions had punished his players for similar incidents) played the main role of provo, and to the dramatization of his character by the long-running Eurinho.
In any case, the debate is about whether this behaviour, which is not expressly prohibited by the statutes, is inconsistent with the principles of sport, i.e. whether these acts constitute a rule of law.
In this case, the damage caused to the sports spirit should be investigated.
The sports spirit defends the physical integrity of the opponents, an aspect that was not compromised by these actions, because it was not an aggressive game.
Another aspect of a clean game is to prevent the opposing players from taking an unjustified advantage from the opposing team. Nor did it happen.
The paradox of the actions of the players of Real Madrid is that it does not correspond to what we usually mean by misplay or rule-making, because circumvention of the rule was not secretly carried out to avoid a penalty, but it should be as conspicuous as possible so that it is punished by the arbitrator.
The players waited and gladly accepted the sanction.
Another question is what kind of advantage the opponents drew from the deliberate fouls.
It should be emphasized here that the rival was neither brought into a more disadvantageous position nor any advantages were heated for the game played, because the obvious result of this action was that the own team had to continue playing with fewer players.
It is also not a useful strategy for the next game, because the club then does not have these players.
The advantage is obviously that players begin the next phase of the Champions League game without cards that could threaten their participation in a future game.
But this is a long-term, up to a certain degree uncertain advantage, as the team could at some point also rule out. In addition, players with this approach receive a penalty and go into the second card cycle, in which they are less out of balance due to card accumulation than in the first cycle.
Thus, it is not clear whether this is really an advantage.
Ultimately, such practices are not directed against the spirit of sport, which also includes strategic decisions in order to make the most of the rules.
In this case, the players did not want to bypass a sanction (that would actually be a clear case of rule-making), they preferred to choose when to submit to it.
They made a strategic decision without escaping a penalty or fleeing from it.
Although the boundary between the invention and the regulatory environment is blurred, I believe that this matter is a clear case of the invention.
I have the impression that the polemic arose as a result of two factors: because it was about two self-exclusions and because of the nature of the provocative rule transmission.
The harm that has been inflicted on the principles of sport by these actions is less ethical than aesthetic.
