China Maintains its Goals to Reduce Greenhouse Gas
The representative of China said at COP16 that his country has made huge efforts to reduce carbon footprint and it would maintain its offer to reduce 40 to 45 percent of its greenhouse gases by 2020.
China maintains its offer to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 40 to 45 percent by 2020, said Su Wei, the country’s representative at COP16.
At his first public appearance at the 16th United Nations Climate Summit (COP16), Su Wei assured that his country would have made enormous efforts to reduce carbon footprints and transform its industry.
He said his country has invested $245 million over the past four years to cut greenhouse gas emissions.
On the other hand, he stated that China would not change its goals, but would work together with the international community on this issue.
He explained that China’s climate change strategy is divided into four aspects: dialogue, capacity-building, institution-building, and support for pilot programmes.
Progress has been made in all aspects, including the adoption of a new energy law last year, which includes the targets for reducing gas emissions, he said.
On the other hand, he pointed out that in China, the federal authorities of the states had worked with those of the central state and the municipalities to achieve the goals of energy saving, efficient use of energy and reduction of emissions.
In addition, he said, some multi-year plans have already been under attack or have been completed, both those funded by the Chinese government and those received funds from other countries.
For example, he referred to the energy efficiency programme, which was introduced in the last five years and had received investments from the United Nations (UN), the government and private hands.
There is also a project on climate change at the provincial level, another to replace traditional light bulbs with energy-saving bulbs, and another to weaken and adapt, he explained.
Martin Krol, the country’s scientific government adviser on climate change, confirmed that China’s efforts would be far greater than generally assumed.
He pointed out that per capita greenhouse gas emissions in China amounted to six tons per person, while in the United States there were 100 tons. China is responsible for a nine percent total contribution to environmental pollution.
In the same way, it is making unprecedented progress in the field of energy use, energy efficiency has increased by 20 percent over the last five years and is expected to be further by 2020, he said.
