The U.S. is changing the rules for obtaining a visa
The persons must present themselves before their meeting with the consulate at the service points for the visa application; the costs will be shortened.
As of January 10, 2011, the procedures for applying for a visa will change in the United States Embassy and Consulates.
In the new procedure, most applicants are required to present themselves before their meeting at the Consulate at the Visa Application Services (ASC, initials in English).
The staff of the ASC shall record the biometric data of the applicant, which shall be checked by the Consulate prior to the interview.
The new procedure has certain advantages for the aspirants, including:
The total cost of processing the visa decreases, since it is no longer necessary to pay separately the appointment, processing the visa application and the transport service with which the document is delivered.
The applicant only makes a single payment covering the three services.
The current price remains unchanged: the equivalent of $140 for a tourist visa, $150 for visa with application (including visa for temporary workers) and $390 for hands and investors.
Those who only want to extend their visa do not need to have a conversation at the consulate, they only need to present themselves at the nearest ASC, where they will present their documents and their fingerprints will be taken.
As the biometric data is collected in the ASC, applicants who need a second date for the conversation in the consulate will remain there less time than before.
Those who apply for the visa at the consulates of Ciudad Ju<0xC3><0xA1>rez, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo no longer have to pay the $26 service fee.
Further information on the new visa application procedure can be found on the following website: http://mexico.usembassy.gov/boletines/sp101201_Visas-FAQs.html
